  "prompt": "Are prunes more likely to make you poop than other kinds of dried fruit? If not, how did they get that association?",
  "response": "Prunes are indeed more likely to make you poop compared to other kinds of dried fruit. This association is supported by scientific evidence and historical use. Prunes contain a high amount of dietary fiber, including both soluble and insoluble fiber, which helps regulate bowel movements. Additionally, prunes have natural sorbitol, a type of sugar alcohol that acts as a mild laxative by drawing water into the intestines, thus promoting bowel movements.\n\nThe association of prunes with alleviating constipation has been well-established over time. They have been used traditionally and recommended in medical practice for their effectiveness in treating constipation. Studies have shown that consuming prunes can improve stool frequency and consistency compared to other laxatives or dietary interventions.\n\nOther dried fruits such as figs, apricots, and raisins also contain fiber and can be beneficial for digestion, but prunes generally have a higher fiber content and the added benefit of sorbitol, making them more effective for promoting bowel movements.\n\nThis combination of historical use, natural composition, and medical evidence is the reason why prunes are particularly associated with aiding digestion and relieving constipation more than other dried fruits.",
